Genus XLIII. VANELLUS. 1. V. Melanogaster (Swiss Sandpiper).

This beautiful bird has been met with several times in the spring of the year at Yarmouth, probably on its passage to its breeding haunts. It has also been killed at the same place late in autumn, at which time it has aequired the plumage usually attributed to the Gray Sandpiper; and it is by no means un- common on the Essex coast throughout the winter. As the plumage upon the upper parts of this bird in autumn is inter- spersed with yellow spots, it assumes at that season a resem- blance to a Golden Plover. And there can be little doubt that it was a Swiss Sandpiper in its autumn dress to which Mr. Mark- wick alludes, when he sayS‚ ‘⁶ I once saw a Golden Plover which had a small back toe.'’—Limz. Trans. vol. iv. pp. 25, 26.
